{"id":14881415,"mediaExerciseId":"24d0ba6e-5632-4747-ab6c-6cd08ffb39c4","exerciseName":"16","chapterName":"13","chapterTitle":"Return, Risk, and The Security Market Line","groupId":612376,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":453,"solutions":[{"id":5997410,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise asks us to determine the risk-free rate using CAPM. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":28,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/428055ecaa638cca62118ffe48b3bcdf/118c2dc1b969f69ea21b666d6f94a034/lateximg_large.png","width":874},"regular":{"height":15,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/428055ecaa638cca62118ffe48b3bcdf/118c2dc1b969f69ea21b666d6f94a034/lateximg.png","width":436}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The **capital asset pricing model (CAPM)** is an equation that shows how systematic risk and expected returns are related. The CAPM informs us that the expected return is influenced by the time value of money, theÂ risk premium, and the stock's beta compared to an average value.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":143,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/428055ecaa638cca62118ffe48b3bcdf/4b1051540120ebf81dcee7b62792be94/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/428055ecaa638cca62118ffe48b3bcdf/4b1051540120ebf81dcee7b62792be94/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"\nLet's first identify the given amounts in the problem: \n\n| | Amount$\\hspace{5pt}$| \n|:--|--:| \n|Expected return | 11.85\\%|\n|Beta| 1.24|\n|Market expected return | 10.2\\%|\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":103,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/428055ecaa638cca62118ffe48b3bcdf/142e285ce0c4aced88992f05e408cdfe/lateximg_large.png","width":1009},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/428055ecaa638cca62118ffe48b3bcdf/142e285ce0c4aced88992f05e408cdfe/lateximg.png","width":506}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"The capital asset pricing model (CAPM) is as follows: \n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{r }_{I}&={\\text{R}_{f}} + {{[B}_{I}}{\\text{ $\\times$ }}{\\text{(R}_{m}} - {\\text{R}_{f}}{)]}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nWhere: \n$$\\begin{aligned}\n{\\text{r}_{I}}& = {\\text{Cost of capital for an investment}} \\\\\n{\\text{R}_{f}}& = {\\text{Risk-free interest rate }} \\\\\n{\\text{R}_{m}}& = {\\text{Market expected return  }} \\\\\n{\\text{B}_{I}} &= {\\text{Beta}} \n\\end{aligned}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":326,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/428055ecaa638cca62118ffe48b3bcdf/14e64ea2048b4fe764effbf0b178222c/lateximg_large.png","width":759},"regular":{"height":164,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/428055ecaa638cca62118ffe48b3bcdf/14e64ea2048b4fe764effbf0b178222c/lateximg.png","width":378}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"First, let us insert the provided data to the formula from step 4. As an illustration, here's what it looks like: \n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{11.85\\%}&={\\text{R}_{f}} + {{[1.24}}{\\text{ $\\times$ }}{\\text{(10.2\\%}} - {\\text{R}_{f}}{)]}\\\\\n\\text{11.85\\%}&={\\text{R}_{f}} +{{12.65\\%}}- {\\text{1.24}}{\\text{R}_{f}}\\\\\n\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"Then, let us rearrange the formula by shifting the risk-free rate to the other side. This is done as follows: \n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\n-{\\text{R}_{f}} &={{12.65\\%}}\\text{ - 11.85\\%}- {\\text{1.24}}{\\text{R}_{f}}\\\\\n-{\\text{R}_{f}} &={\\text{0.80\\%}}- {\\text{1.24}}{\\text{R}_{f}}\\\\\n-{\\text{R}_{f}} + {\\text{1.24}}{\\text{R}_{f}} &={\\text{0.80\\%}}\\\\\n {\\text{0.24}}{\\text{R}_{f}} &={\\text{0.80\\%}}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"Then, let us divide both sides by the coefficient of 0.24. This is to cancel out the coefficient of the risk-free rate. This is computed as follows: \n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\n {\\text{0.24}}{\\text{R}_{f}} &={\\text{0.80\\%}}\\\\\n\\dfrac {{\\text{0.24}}{\\text{R}_{f}}}{\\text{0.24}} &=\\dfrac{\\text{0.80\\%}}\n{\\text{0.24}}\\\\\n{\\text{R}_{f}}&={\\textbf{3.33\\%}}\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":7},{"columns":[{"text":"**To conclude, the risk-free rate is 3.33\\%.**","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":30,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/428055ecaa638cca62118ffe48b3bcdf/6d6709a30c2bcac02d6568f9f6ae2673/lateximg_large.png","width":585},"regular":{"height":15,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/428055ecaa638cca62118ffe48b3bcdf/6d6709a30c2bcac02d6568f9f6ae2673/lateximg.png","width":294}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":8}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"980a5719-46c7-4f4d-9299-a5c4485ec95c","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":8}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Co